sec.p:
This paper reports on findings from an Australia-wide sentencing and public confidence project, which, in its entirety will generate much needed quantitative as well as qualitative data on the critical issue of public confidence in sentencing through a multi-phased research design. The objectives of this project as a whole were as follows:


To comprehensively measure the levels of public confidence in the way in which judges and magistrates sentence offenders in Australian courts;

To analyse the socio-demographic, cultural, cognitive and attitudinal predictors (e.g. knowledge and beliefs about crime and sentencing, fear of crime) relevant to ‘public confidence’;

To assess the malleability of confidence levels as a measure of likely public tolerance and support for the development of reform initiatives;

To analyse and examine the stability of punitive attitudes over time; and

To apply small group methodology to assess ways in which public opinion can be ascertained in a form that can be utilised to inform sentencing practice.
